36. Sygambros (otherwise called Sicambri). This was a German tribe which inhabited the eastern bank of the Rhine, in the region now known as the Rhenish Provinces (the name is possibly preserved in that of the river Sieg). They invaded Gallia Belgica in B.C. 16, and defeated the legatus, M. Lollius. Augustus, who seems to have been greatly disturbed by the disaster, lest Rome to take command of the operations which were intended to retrieve it. Before he arrived, however, the Sygambri made peace and retired to their own country. They were subdued by Rome, but not till some years after the writing of this ode.
